Experiment No. 2: Setup of Wired LAN Using Layer 2 Switch
üß† 1. Understanding the Experiment
Aim

To set up a wired Local Area Network (LAN) using a Layer 2 Switch, including:

Preparation and crimping of network cables (Cat5/Cat6)

Testing cables using a line tester

Assigning IP addresses to connected systems

Testing connectivity with the PING command

Analyzing network packets using Wireshark Packet Analyzer

Objectives

Understand the structure and working of wired LANs and the devices involved.

Gain hands-on experience in making, testing, and troubleshooting Ethernet cables.

Learn to verify network connectivity and capture packet data for analysis.

Key Concepts & Theoretical Background
1. Local Area Network (LAN)

A LAN connects computers and devices within a limited area like a classroom, office, or lab.

Devices in a LAN can share data, printers, and internet resources.

Typically includes switches, cables, network interface cards (NICs), and computers.

2. Types of Networks
Type	Full Form	Range	Example
LAN	Local Area Network	Small area (office/lab)	Campus or building network
MAN	Metropolitan Area Network	City-wide	City government network
WAN	Wide Area Network	Large area (country/world)	The Internet
3. Transmission Media

Medium through which data travels:

Wired Media ‚Äì Twisted Pair, Coaxial, Fiber Optic

Wireless Media ‚Äì Radio, Infrared, Microwaves

Types of Wired Media:
Type	Description	Speed	Common Use
UTP (Unshielded Twisted Pair)	4 pairs of twisted copper wires	Up to 1 Gbps	LAN connections
STP (Shielded Twisted Pair)	Each pair shielded to reduce interference	Up to 10 Gbps	Industrial networks
Coaxial Cable	Central copper conductor + metal shield	Up to 100 Mbps	Older LANs, CCTV
Fiber Optic Cable	Transmits data as light signals	>10 Gbps	Long-distance, high-speed links
